,Recommended,269770,18465813,"Posted: 13 October, 2015",all,Astebrooke,"This game is what I've been missing since the advent of the Nintendo 64 and Playstation.  A quality, amusing, fun, multiplayer RPG that lets you be who you want to be and play with your friends.  A lot of the game is simple enough to pick up, while other aspects seem frustratingly incomprehensible (at first).The Good:Can choose the colors of your character's clothes and hair to stand out from other playersCan change your character's hairstyle to stand out as wellCan not only equip masks to look different, but can equip a ""style"" for masks, weapons, and shields, to allow your character to look a certain way without sacrificing the stats on their gear.  Major props to the developers for that mechanic.Humor.  This game has plenty of it.Active developers who read their forums and respond to feedback.  They not only tell you what they're doing every week, they show images and animated gifs that prove it's not just hot air.Experience Cap - You can avoid outleveling your friends by hunting in areas that are beneath you, so you get money and items but no XP.Arcade Mode - A randomly generated series of rooms that let you play a character with your friends and work toward the development of a town.Puzzles - The Temple of Seasons especially.  The use of seasons to not only affect the monsters' abilities, but also affect what can be done with the room, is amazingly well done.  Some of the other puzzles (like the bells) require a little attention to detail to figure out.  includes puzzle-related humor as well.Fishing - Because fish!  Ok, because it's a free way to get pet food, and the time investment doesn't make it feel cheaty for the return.Pets! - Because pets!  They don't fight for you, but you can increase your stats by feeding your pets certain items/fish.  The more they level the more food it will take, so you may wish to devote specific pets to specific traits.The Not-so-Good:Characters only ever have one clothing style, regardless of colors.  Perhaps my character wants to run around in robes, while my brother's wants to run around in a martial arts outfit like the monks in Evergrind.  What if my friend's female character wants to wer a dress, impractical as they are for adventuring?  Male or female, you only get one (the same) set of clothes.Small development team - While not really a bad thing, it does make the updates take a lot longer.  I applaud their desire to keep with a stable core that isn't going to lose interest and disappear during a project, but at the same time I wish they could produce updates just a little faster.  The forums show multiple offers of assistance, which are politely declined.Arcade Mode - Every time you die, you start over at level 1.  This doesn't make for a ""grind"" as much as a monotonous loop of re-leveling and trying to get back to where you had been.  While being too weak in the story mode allows you to backtrack and level, or hunt cards, the Arcade Mode forces you to keep moving into progressively more dangerous territory, and one bad spawn can reset you to zero instead of just backing off and leveling some more.Equipment limitations - With a good drop on one of the bosses you can have one of the best 1-h weapons in the current release of the game, halfway into Story Mode.  Most caster gear is functionally limited until far into the second temple, while you can get great melee armor and weapons throughout.  Even buying all gear and dropping/crafting allarmors as of the end of the current release, some of the most useful caster gear was either available 1/3 of the way into the game (MP regen robes) or at the end of current content (temple loot/drops).Monster Cards - While I do believe they are awesome and useful, I feel the benefits they grant are so powerful in some cases that you become reliant on them, rather than simply empowered by them.  To change them now might require some major balance tweaks, but Bloomo and Pecko are the two that spring to mind.  Without them I stood little chance alone in the Temple of Seasons against the mini-boss, after XP slowed to a crawl.  It seems awkward relying on those to beat a few fights...  Later in the game, unless more high-HP boosting cards are added to balance tough fights, I could see them being less useful.  For now though, they're pretty much a necessity.Economy - It never really seems like you have to worry about money in this game.  By the time I stopped hunting all the cards and mob drops, I had enough money to raise my Jumpkin to level 10 purely off potions.  Buying anything else was like picking out pocket lint, for all the impact it made in my savings.I believe that the game has incredible potential, and is great fun as it stands now.  I've put in 41.2 hours as of the time of this writing, and most if it is in Story Mode.  I probably won't be gaining much on my play time until they release more, but I keep checking the devblog every week for updates.Pixel Ferrets, I salute your game.  Keep at it."
,Recommended,269770,21349002,"Posted: 20 February, 2016",all,MOUSAK LULU,"This might be catching your interest, and it definitely is very interesting. Even though they still are on early access, then they made a really good job on keeping me going with this game. I usually don't enjoy singleplayer games, so i only play Local Co-op with my girlfriend.OBS!!! FOR THOSE WHO ARE INTERESTED IN LOCAL CO-OP!!There is just one little thing that made me frustrated. That is how to fix the Local Co-op mode. I had to search around a bit until I found it. You have to download something called steam_appid.txt which you can find on this link down here: (file is from a staff member called Teddy)http://secretsofgrindea.com/forum/index.php?threads/local-co-op-on-2-computers.913/Put it in the ...Steam\steamapps\common\SecretsOfGrindea folder. Then you have to run 2 windows at one time and do some other things in order to make each controller locked for each window you opened. You'll find more out on the steps that you will be following in the guide on that page!It works really good when you get everything to work! I play on two different monitors at the same time, my laptop screen and TV screen using HDMI cable. Works really well! You can also have two windows running in a single monitor ofc, or 4 windows if you would like that. It has its cons and pros ofc.GL & HF!"
76561198047977354,Recommended,269770,33905692,Posted: 30 July,all,Euphoria,"Secrets of Grindea 8/10As the name suggests, Secrets of Grindea has a LOT to grind. Being purely luck based, the game could have you playing for hours on end without getting what you want, or simply getting it too quickly. Secrets of Grindea, if I had to explain it in the shortest way possible, I'd say this: Completionist's Wet Dream. Why do I say that? Well, continue reading and you'll see why.Early Access: 10/10The reason I'm giving Early Access a 10/10, is because the developer has and continues to update the game, and allows us to see the process in which he is doing it, shows us what he is doing and tells us what he has planned for the future. He promised a housing system when I first got the game, one of the lastest patches gave us that housing system, with enough furniture for me to be pleased. This is what Early Access games should be like.Fighting: 8/10Fighting is 90% of what you will be doing in the game. Although there are different things such as Fishing and Housing System, the game is centered around its fighting. It starts off simple, the game gives you your first weapons, a one-handed sword, a two-handed club and a shield. Now, different to the fighting system in most games, you get to use the shield for both. The Two-Handed weapons, and the One-Handed weapons contain different abilities you can learn through the game, 5 abilities for each, allowing you to polish your fighting style. In the future, you may also specialize in magic, having to choose from four different elements: Fire, Ice, Earth and Air.Personally, I was a bit sad there were no classes in the game, but at the same time you may build your character however you want without any sort of limitation. I loved the fighting, nonetheless. I'll say it's one of the funnest fighting systems. More in-depth explanation in ""Talent System""Talent System: 8.5/10The Talent System is very easy to use. One-Handed and Two-Handed get a certain amount of abilities, which you will be upgrading as you level up. So the Talent System has multiple points you can utilize, one you can use on your abilities, in a basic matter (1-5) and from there you use another point, called the Golden point (5-10) which enhances your ability. I personally felt the two-handed and one-handed played very differently.The last point, the third one is used on your passives. This is where you decide whether your character is tanky, by giving it +%HP or building your character crit damage, even Magic Attack. If you end up regreting your decision, you can click the ability and refund, which will cost you a bit of gold. You will be getting a lot of gold if you stick around to grind for everything.Grinding: 10/10With that being said, let's move onto the grinding. The grinding in this game, is fantastic. Giving you multiple things to finish, farm, and complete. This is why I said, a completionist will love this game. Every zone has 5 fish which you can catch, it is very fun and fish are good for use in the future.When you get your pet, you feed fish, or the items animals drop to make it stronger.Aside from the fishing in every zone, every monster in the game has a very low drop rate to their ""card"" .. These cards, give you permanent boosts, some to your magic attack, some to simple things like extra discount on items you buy. The most common card being a 0.3% droprate. If you dedicate yourself to getting all of these cards, it will increase your gametime exponentially.Controls: 9/10The controls in this game are very simple. You move with the arrow keys, attack with Z and block with X. Your abilities also being close to the Z and X for easier reaction time (C, A, S, D, V, F, Q, W, E, R) All the keys being modifiable, and controller support making it great.Misc: 10/10The Mechanics are very interesting. When you pick up an item of interest (Armor or Weapon) it will appear on the top right, comparing it to the item you have equipped. If you wish to equip your picked up item, you press Tab and ta-da! Your item has been equipped.As for the menu, while you'll be going there a lot to check your talents, and there is no specific button to open it, it's extremely easy to navigate. Separated into 8 categories (Character, Equipment, Inventory, Crafting, Skills, Journal, World Map, System.) the game is easy to work around. Realistically speaking, you'll be using a maximum of 4 of those 8, but it's still nice to be able to see your character's stats.Everything you equip in the game can be changed into an item you own. If you have a two-handed weapon you like the way it looks, but it's weaker, you can equip it as ""Style"" and it will replace your current weapon. It's the same with your Hat, Facegear and Shield. And if you are not the type of person to care for it, you may always hide it by right-clicking on the original item.The Housing System is great, but I will warn you now, it takes a lot of money. It's great because you may make it as big as you want (As far as I've seen, I haven't tested the limit but I have spent over 50k gold on it) with upcoming furniture and a very intuitive system to change the house around, allowing you to change even the lighting on different rooms, to how you want your house's structure to be. Keep in mind, the game is still beta and housing is still not perfect, missing some furniture to fill your house perfectly, you will get more furniture as you complete more dungeons.Co-op in the game works beautifully, with a very easy to set-up server for newbies, it's just a point and click with multiple options, You may set the loot to Round-Robin or Every man for himself, where you just run to get the items, first come, first serve. With an Arcade Mode that I haven't truly gotten around to trying and an arena zone, where you can play Player vs. Player, or unite all to try and kill waves of monsters, getting graded by your time and damage you took, making it interesting to have everyone screaming at each other because a person got tickled by a monster and now you can't get that perfect S.The difficulty is flexible and can be changed inside the game, even during a fight. I wasn't much of a fan on the hard aspect of the game, because I never truly liked bullet hells, and it definitely turns the boss fights into just that. But if it gets too difficult, you can always go back to normal difficulty.Story: 6.5/10And last, but not least, the story in this game is pretty basic. Without getting too much into detail, you can play with your friends through it all, it adds no change, apart from the fact that you need to farm for more cards per player. I couldn't get into the story, some very funny characters I enjoyed interacting with, some I couldn't wait to get off my back. I laughed a lot in the dialogue, that I won't lie about. The con of the game, for me, was the storyline. But it did not make the gameplay through the story unenjoyable, I just prefered the aspects of farming in the game."
