,Not Recommended,269770,33015171,Posted: 29 June,all,Kivorkian,"First of all, this is an early access game and should be undstood as such; however the beta was pushed out in 2013 according to their dev blog.  With that said, below is a review based on my time playing the game and my concerns regarding its future development.*Note: This review does not include the multiplayer or arcade aspects and this should be taken into consideration when reading this review.1.) Visuals: 3/5- Reminiscent of Super Nintendo games such as The Legend of Zelda, Star Dew Valley and Secret of Mana but nothing new or exciting to the visual experience.- Animations are very basic but do not add to the genre.2.) Mechanics: 3/5- Follows the same templates as older SNES adventure/RPG titles and adds a little bit of depth to the real-time combat with the talent trees and progression systems but doesn't do much to seperate itself from other finished titles.3.) Sound: 3/5- Music is well done and helps to serve the landscape equally as well.- Sound Effects are basic and satisfy the requirements.4.) Story: 1/5- It's basic at best and unfinished at worst.5.) Overall: 3/5- The game isn't good but isn't bad and doesn't add to the genre.  It feels more like a rebuild of older SNES games with features picked from each to replicate what Nintendo has done to it's fans for decades (ie: selling nostalgia.)  From the visuals to the sound, the game offers little to be excited about since the story is unfinished (ie: restrictions from proceeding forward to the end of the game's story.)  If you're seeking a game that takes you back to the early 90s then this may be the game for you but expect to only get a few hours out of it before you get bored and move on.Concerns:- The dev team seems to be all over the place with no real plan for completing the game.  I say this because the game is full of features... and that's pretty much it since no single element feels complete.- Development started in 2011, Beta released in 2013, Early Accessed in 2015, Release date Still TBD... I don't attribute this to laziness but instead is a byproduct of likely poor understanding of tools, workflows and project management overall.- The dev team wants to polish the game as they go.  This means that they will have an extremely slow release cycle of impactful content since they keep revisiting and re-polishing the game over and over and over again."
